06684nam a22009735i 9789048552139DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485521397 a10.1515/97890485521392doi  a(DE-B1597)637771  a(OCoLC)1371573359  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aARC0050402bisacsh00aConnected Mobilities in the Early Modern World :bThe Practice and Experience of Movement /ced. by Rosa Salzberg, Paul Nelles. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aConnected Histories in the Early Modern World ;v700tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tMovement and Mobility in the Early Modern World : An Introduction -- tMoving Bodies -- t1. Linguistic Encounter : Fynes Moryson and the Uses of Language -- t2. Wading Through the Mire : Mobility on the Grand Tour (1585–1750) -- t3. Travelling for Health : Medicine and Rural Mobility in Early Modern Spain -- tCrossing Borders -- t4. Mobility and Danger on the Borders of the Papal States (Sixteenth-Seventeenth Centuries) -- t5. News on the Road : The Mobility of Handwritten Newsletters in Early Modern Europe -- t6. Quarantine, Mobility, and Trade : Commercial Lazzarettos in the Early Modern Adriatic -- tGlobal Networks -- t7. Devotion in Transit : Agnus Dei, Jesuit Missionaries, and Global Salvation in the Sixteenth Century -- t8. Getting to the Holy Land : Franciscan Journeys and Mediterranean Mobility -- t9. From Mount Lebanon to the Little Mount in Madras : Mobility and Catholic-Armenian Alms-Collecting Networks During the Eighteenth Century -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book offers a panorama of movement, mobility, and exchange in the early modern world. While the pre-modern centuries have long been portrayed as static and self-contained, it is now acknowledged that Europe from the Middle Ages onwards saw increasing flows of people and goods. Movement also connected the continent more closely to other parts of the world. The present work challenges dominant notions of the ‘fixed,’ immobile nature of pre-modern cultures through study of the inter-connected material, social, and cultural dimensions of mobility. The case studies presented here chart the technologies and practices that both facilitated and impeded movement in diverse spheres of social activity such as communication, transport, politics, religion, medicine, and architecture. The chapters underscore the importance of the movement of people and objects through space and across distance to the dynamic economic, political, and cultural life of the early modern period.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aInterdisciplinary Studies. 4aInternational Relations. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  amobility, travel, networks, material culture, early modern Europe, global history.1 aAslanian, Sebouh David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBilić, Darka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFosi, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGallagher, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMolino, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelles, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNelles, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSalzberg, Rosa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSalzberg, Rosa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.l